The 29-year-old man accused of killing the Normandien farm couple outside Newcastle in the northern KwaZulu-Natal has appeared at the local magistrate’s court. The accused, Siyabonga Macu is facing two charges of murder and robbery. The accused initially told the court he will be representing himself. However after failing to engage the court Macu opted for a legal aid. #sabcnews #sabckzn The accused in the double murder of the Normandien farm couple in Newcastle on the northern KwaZulu-Natal has briefly appeared in the local court and matter postponed. pic.twitter.com/s5vnzV6oQg — Nonkululeko Hlophe (@Leko3) September 21, 2020  The state told the court this is a schedule six offence and they will be opposing bail. It is alleged that Macu shot and killed Vida and Glen Rafferty as they entered their farm house three weeks ago. The case has been postponed to the 28th of September for bail application. #sabcnews #sabckzn Community of Normandien including farmers and farm dwellers are currently in a meeting with Police Minister Bheki Cele. It is the area where the farm couple Vida and Glen Rafferty were killed last month outside Newcastle in northern KwaZulu-Natal. pic.twitter.com/yDcQCg58Fv — Nonkululeko Hlophe (@Leko3) September 21, 2020  Bikers against  farm murders On Saturday bikers against farm murders embarked on a mass ride to the Union Buildings in Tshwane, Gauteng to take a stand against gender-based violence, racism, and farm murders. White crosses and roses were laid at the lawns of the Union Buildings, paying tribute to farmers who have lost their lives violently. The bikers embarked on a 50km mass ride Saturday morning before making their way to the seat of government. In the video below the bikers speak to SABC News 